In [33]:
# define maximum likelihood estimate for this training set
def max_lik_estimate(X, y):
    # X: N=404 x D=18 matrix of training inputs
    # y: N=404 x 1 vector of training targets/observations
    # returns: maximum likelihood parameters (D=18 x 1)
    N, D = X.shape
    beta_ml = np.linalg.solve(X.T @ X, X.T @ y)
    return beta_ml

We use the maximum liekelihood estimate to get the parameters beta of the model

In [35]:
# define the prediction function for linear regression
def predict_with_estimate(X_test, beta):
    # X_test: K x D matrix of test inputs
    # beta: D x 1 vector of parameters
    # returns: prediction of f(X_test); K x 1 vector 
    prediction = X_test @ beta
    return prediction

Finally, we get the prediction and calculate the in-sample mean squared error (MSE)

Getting a MSE of around 24 makes sense when we look at the values of the dependent variable y_train, the last column in the full training dataset, as their mean is around 20 and the data points range from 7 to the largest outlier being 50. Moreover, a larger in-sample MSE having removed the collinear rows suggests a reduction in overfitting, so we will proceed to work with the removed columns.

As a plus, compute the condition numbers of the matrices with collinear columns and without collinear columns:

In [39]:
X_cond = np.linalg.cond(X_train)
print('not eliminated',X_cond)
X_cond_e = np.linalg.cond(X_train_elim)
print('eliminated',X_cond_e)

not eliminated 1.5685751557079054e+16
eliminated 6.094416963408895

We now clearly see that the condition number of the training data with collinear columns is much larger. This shows that the taking the inverse $(X^T X)^{-1}$ which is needed in the solution for the beta terms in linear regression will result in larger variance.

We will explicitly check that when we evaluate whether the elimination reduces the out-of-sample error in the next subsection.

Now, check whether we can get a smaller error by standardising the data.

In [16]:
# function to standardize X_train_elim and X_test_elim
def standardise(X):
    mu = np.mean(X, 0)
    sigma = np.std(X, 0)
    X_std = (X - mu) / sigma
    return X_std

1.1.2.¶

In this subsection, we will use the test data to test the model to predict the target variable, compute the out-of-sample MSE on the test set. We will then compare to the in-sample MSE and explain the differences.

In [44]:
# make a prediction using the MLE
out_pred = predict_with_estimate(X_test, beta_ml)
# out-sample mean squared error (MSE)
mse_out = np.square(np.subtract(y_test,out_pred)).mean()
print('out-of-sample MSE for test set with collinear columns',mse_out)

out-of-sample MSE for test set with collinear columns 19.557330193706065
In [45]:
# out-sample MSE, eliminated colinear columns
out_pred_elim = predict_with_estimate(X_test_elim, beta_ml_elim)
mse_out_elim = np.square(np.subtract(y_test,out_pred_elim)).mean()
print('out-of-sample MSE for test set, eliminated collinear columns:',mse_out_elim)

out-of-sample MSE for test set, eliminated collinear columns: 19.360481532901694

The first observation is that the out-of-sample MSE for both matrices is smaller than the in-sample MSE. This is arguably because we have less rows in the test set than the train set and the model works better.

Moreover, we know that collinearity produces overfitting and we see that indeed for the train and test sets with all columns (some of which are collinear), we have a smaller in-sample MSE and a larger out-of-sample MSE than for the train and test sets where we eliminate the collinear columns. This shows that the model trained with collinear columns tends to overfit and has errors due to the large condition number of the training matrix. It is also nicer because in addition to getting more accurate predictions, we have less data to train on - the computations are faster.

Define the function that computes maximum likelihood parameters.

In [47]:
def ridge_estimate(X, y, penalty):
    # X: N x D matrix of training inputs
    # y: N x 1 vector of training targets/observations
    # returns: maximum likelihood parameters (D x 1)
    N, D = X.shape
    I = np.identity(D)
    beta_ridge = np.linalg.solve(X.T @ X + penalty * I, X.T @ y)
    return beta_ridge

Define the functions that will allow us to do the splitting into folds and evaluate the model.

In [47]:
def cross_val_split(data, num_folds):
    fold_size = int(len(data) / num_folds)
    data_perm = np.random.RandomState(seed=1007).permutation(data) # set the seed to always have the same random permutations
    folds = []
    for k in range(num_folds):
        folds.append(data_perm[k*fold_size:(k+1)*fold_size, :])
    return folds
In [49]:
def cross_val_evaluate(data, num_folds, penalty_term, X_test, y_test):  # the y_test needs to be shuffled the same as the folds
  
    folds = cross_val_split(data, num_folds)
    
    # define this list for each penalty term, it collects the 5 MSEs
    val_mses = []
    test_mses = []

    for i in range(len(folds)):
        # define the training set
        train_set = np.delete(np.asarray(folds).reshape(len(folds), folds[0].shape[0], folds[0].shape[1]), i, axis=0)
        train_folds = train_set.reshape(len(train_set)*train_set[0].shape[0], train_set[0].shape[1])
    
        X_train = train_folds[:,:-1]
        y_train = train_folds[:,-1]
    
        # define the validation set
        val_fold = folds[i]
        X_val = val_fold[:,:-1]
        y_val = val_fold[:,-1]

        # train on all folds except k with penalty p - get beta_ridge
        beta_ridge = ridge_estimate(X_train, y_train, penalty=penalty_term)
        
        # calculate prediction on fold k with penalty p - get ridge_prediction
        ridge_prediction_val = predict_with_estimate(X_val, beta_ridge)
        # evaluate the MSE on the validation set
        val_mse = np.square(np.subtract(y_val,ridge_prediction_val)).mean()

        # append the validation MSE to the list containing the MSEs for each fold
        val_mses.append(val_mse)
        
        # calculate prediction for test set, evaluate the MSE on the test set
        ridge_prediction_test = predict_with_estimate(X_test, beta_ridge)
        test_mse = np.square(np.subtract(y_test,ridge_prediction_test)).mean()
        test_mses.append(test_mse) # append
    
    return np.array(val_mses), np.array(test_mses)

Scan over penalty parameters, save the validation MSEs in a matrix with rows corresponding to each candidate parameter, and 5 columns corresponding to each of the 5 validation folds. The number of columns is therefore 5 in our case.

In [51]:
# candidate penalty terms
p_term = np.arange(0.0,28,0.01)

ERR_val = np.zeros((len(p_term),5))
ERR_test = np.zeros((len(p_term),5))

# shuffle the data (X and y stacked together)
data_ridge = data1.copy()
random.seed(1007)
random.shuffle(data_ridge)


# fill the MSE matrix
p_i=0
for p in p_term:
    val_mses, test_mses = cross_val_evaluate(data_ridge, 5, p, X_test, y_test)
    ERR_val[p_i,:] = val_mses
    ERR_test[p_i,:] = test_mses
    p_i+=1
        
print('Shape of the matrix containing the MSEs for each fold for each candidate penalty term',ERR_val.shape)

Shape of the matrix containing the MSEs for each fold for each candidate penalty term (2800, 5)

Get optimal penalty terms, plot for the first fold

In [469]:
def get_optimal_penalty(ERR,p_term,val_fold_index):    
    mse_fold = ERR[:,val_fold_index]
    
    minp1=np.min(mse_fold)
    print('Minimal value of validation MSE, fold '+str(val_fold_index+1)+':', minp1)
    
    opt_p = p_term[np.argmin(mse_fold)]
    print('Optimal penalty term validation fold '+str(val_fold_index+1)+':',opt_p,'\n')
    if val_fold_index==0:
        plt.plot(p_term,mse_fold,'.')
        plt.title('search for penalty term that minimises the MSE, validation fold 1')
        plt.xlabel('candidate penalty terms')
        plt.ylabel('MSE')
        plt.show()
    return opt_p

p_optimal = []
for i in range(5):
    p1 = get_optimal_penalty(ERR_val,p_term,i)
    p_optimal.append(p1)

print('Optimal penalty parameter for each 5-fold',p_optimal)

1.2.2.¶

Compute average in-sample MSE (using validation MSE):

1) Compute the MSE of each validation fold for each candidate penalty term

2) Take the average of these MSEs to get the average MSE for the specific candidate penalty term

3) Choose the optimal penalty where the average MSE is minimum across all candidate penalty terms

In [470]:
# calculate the average validation MSE over the 5 folds for each candidate penalty term
mse_avg_val = (1/5)*ERR_val.sum(axis=1)

# find the optimal penalty term to get the smallest average MSE over the 5 folds
minp_in=np.min(mse_avg_val)
print('Average in-sample validation MSE over 5 folds\n\nMinimum value of validation MSE',minp_in)
# print('\nminimum at index',np.argmin(mse_avg))
p_opt = p_term[np.argmin(mse_avg_val)]
print('\nOptimal penalty term',p_opt)
plt.plot(p_term,mse_avg_val,'.')
plt.title('search for optimal penalty term with validation MSE, 5 fold avg')
plt.xlabel('candidate penalty terms')
plt.ylabel('validation MSE')
plt.show()

Average in-sample validation MSE over 5 folds

print(in_mse1)


# calculate prediction on test set
ridge_prediction2 = predict_with_estimate(X_test, beta_ridge1)
# evaluate the MSE on the test set
in_mse2 = np.square(np.subtract(y_test,ridge_prediction2)).mean()
print(in_mse2)

In-sample: using Ridge regression, we get a larger in-sample MSE than linear regression in part 1.1.2.

Out-of-sample: using Ridge regression, we get a slightly smaller out-of-sample MSE than linear regression in part 1.1.2.

This clearly shows that Ridge regression indeed reduces overfitting that we get with linear regression. This is because compared to linear regression, Ridge is a bit worse (larger MSE) for the train set and, crucially, performs better on an unseen test set (smaller MSE). However, even though it is an improvement, it is not as significant as we would expect.

1.3 Regression with kNN¶

1.3.1.¶

Recall that the dataset we are using has the collinear columns eliminated so as to reduce overfitting - this is also valid for kNN because when we have collinear predictors (columns), the values in the predictor are close to each other and this will lead to smaller k values, which implies overfitting.

First, we define the functions we will use to implement the kNN algorithm.

In [52]:
def euclidian_distance(p, q):
    return np.sqrt(np.sum((p-q)**2, axis=1))


def k_neighbours(X_test, X_train_stack, k, return_distance=False):
  n_neighbours = k
  dist = []
  neigh_ind = []
  
  # compute distance from each point x_text in X_test to all points in X_train (hint: use python's list comprehension)
  point_dist = [euclidian_distance(x_test, X_train_stack) for x_test in X_test]

  # determine which k training points are closest to each test point
  for row in point_dist:
      enum_neigh = enumerate(row)
      sorted_neigh = sorted(enum_neigh, key=lambda x: x[1])[:k]

      ind_list = [tup[0] for tup in sorted_neigh]
      dist_list = [tup[1] for tup in sorted_neigh]

      dist.append(dist_list)
      neigh_ind.append(ind_list)
  
  # return distances together with indices of k nearest neighbouts
  if return_distance:
      return np.array(dist), np.array(neigh_ind)
  
  return np.array(neigh_ind)


def reg_predict(X_test, y_train, X_train_stack, k):
  # each of the k neighbours contributes equally to the classification of any data point in X_test  
  neighbours = k_neighbours(X_test, X_train_stack, k)
  # compute mean over neighbours labels (hint: use python's list comprehension)
  y_pred = np.array([np.mean(y_train[neighbour]) for neighbour in neighbours])
  return y_pred


def r2_score(y_test, y_pred):
  numerator = np.sum((y_test - y_pred)**2)
  y_avg = np.mean(y_test)
  denominator = np.sum((y_test - y_avg)**2)
  return 1 - numerator/denominator

In the cross-validation, we save the R2 error, the average in-sample and out-of-sample MSEs in matrices of the same form as in the CV for Ridge regression. The rows represent the candidate parameters, and the columns represent the folds over which we train the training data for that candidate parameter.

In [53]:
k_arr = np.arange(1,20)  # candidate k's

def cross_val_evaluate(data, num_folds):
  
    folds = cross_val_split(data, num_folds)
    k_arr = np.arange(1,20)  # candidate k's
    print('candidate ks:',k_arr)

    R2 = np.zeros((len(k_arr),5))  # matrix to contain the r2 scores
    ERR_in = np.zeros((len(k_arr),5))  # to contain the validation MSEs
    ERR_out = np.zeros((len(k_arr),5)) # for out-of-sample MSEs
    
    
    for i in range(len(folds)):
#         print('Fold', i+1)
        # define the training set
        train_set = np.delete(np.asarray(folds).reshape(len(folds), folds[0].shape[0], folds[0].shape[1]), i, axis=0)
        train_folds = train_set.reshape(len(train_set)*train_set[0].shape[0], train_set[0].shape[1])
        X_train = train_folds[:,:-1]
        y_train = train_folds[:,-1]
    
        # define the validation set
        val_fold = folds[i]
        X_val = val_fold[:,:-1]
        y_val = val_fold[:,-1]
        
        # iterate through the k's
        j=0  # row index for each candidate k
        for k in k_arr:
            # predict on validation set
            y_pred = reg_predict(X_val, y_train, X_train, k)  # get prediction for knn-neighbors for train set without fold i
            # R2 score
            r2 = r2_score(y_val, y_pred)  # calculate the r2 score for knn-neighbors for fold i as validation set 
            R2[j,i] = r2
            # validation MSE in-sample
            mse_in = np.square(np.subtract(y_val,y_pred)).mean()
            ERR_in[j,i] = mse_in
            
            # predict on the test set, out-of-sample
            y_pred = reg_predict(X_test, y_train, X_train, k)
            mse_out = np.square(np.subtract(y_test,y_pred)).mean()
            ERR_out[j,i] = mse_out            
            j+=1
            
    return R2, ERR_in, ERR_out

1.3.2.¶

We now analyse the in-sample and out-of-sample MSE to determine the optimal k:

In [491]:

plt.plot(k_arr,mse_avg_in,'.',label='in-sample')

plt.plot(k_arr,mse_avg_out,'.',label='out-of-sample')

Minimal in-sample MSE at optimal k = 2 , averaged over the 5 folds: 4.61993125

Minimal out-of-sample MSE at optimal k = 4 , averaged over the 5 folds: 14.627162990196078

This is significantly better than the linear or Ridge regression, importantly, there is a reduction from 19.17 to 14.627 in the out-of-sample MSE. Note that the kNN can reduce overfitting, for a suitable choice of k.

We get the relatively small optimal k=2 in the in-sample MSE, because the training set has been memorised in this case and we have overfitted the data, clearly having k=2 results in overfitting in the out-of-sample MSE. Even more so if we choose k=1, where the out-of-sample MSE is largest. This, again, is because we have high accuracy but high variance.

As we increase k seekin glower variance, we are tweaking the bias-variance balance and get lower accuracy (higher bias). This is reflected in the increasing in-sample MSE values as we increase k. However, looking at the out-of-sample MSE, we see that it is significantly smaller for k=3,4,5 than for k=1,2, suggesting we are decreasing the variance (at the cost of bias/accuracy). Our cross-validation results suggest that the optimal parameter k that minimises the out-of-sample MSE is k=4.

Therefore, I would take k=3 or k=4 for a reasonable bias-variance balance. Let us check whether these values of k are indeed the optimal for the testing set.

In [64]:

The minimal value of the MSE for the test set is 12.530446623093683 at k = 3

The reason why kNN works so much better may be that our data is non-linear (predictors are non-linearly distributed), thus local methods such as kNN are better-suited to work with rather than linear methods that were shown to produce MSEs that are almost twice as large.

Moreover, if we had not cleaned the data from collinear columns, we probably have gotten a smaller value of k as optimal foro the training set, which would lead to overfitting as the data would be more clustered in this case. This justifies removing the collinear columns.

# standardize the X_train and X_test
def standardise(X):
  mu = np.mean(X, 0)
  sigma = np.std(X, 0)
  X_std = (X - mu) / sigma
  return X_std

X_train = standardise(X_train)
X_test = standardise(X_test)

2.1. Logistic Regression¶

2.1.1.¶

In this subsection, we implement logistic regression for classification with gradient descent for 5000 iterations; and perform a grid-search with 5-fold cross validation to find optimal set of hyperparameters: learning rate and decision threshold.

First, we define the functions to implement the logistic regression model.

In [14]:
# define the functions we will need in this part for logistic regression
def logistic(x):
    return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-x))


def predict_log(X, beta, beta_0):
    y_log = logistic(beta.T @ X + beta_0)
    return y_log


def initialise(d):
    beta = np.zeros(shape=(d, 1), dtype=np.float32)
    beta_0 = 0
    assert(beta.shape==(d, 1))
    assert(isinstance(beta_0, float) or isinstance(beta_0, int))
    return beta, beta_0


def propagate(X, y, beta, beta_0):
    n = X.shape[1]
    y_log = predict_log(X, beta, beta_0)

    # cost function
    cost = (-1) * np.mean(np.multiply(y, np.log(y_log)) + np.multiply(1-y, np.log(1 - y_log)), axis=1)

    # derivatives
    dbeta = (1/n) * X @ np.transpose(y_log - y)
    dbeta_0 =  np.mean((y_log - y)) 

    assert(dbeta.shape==beta.shape)
    assert(dbeta_0.dtype==float)
    cost = np.squeeze(cost)
    assert(cost.shape==())

    # store gradients in a dictionary
    grads = {"dbeta": dbeta, "dbeta_0": dbeta_0}

    return grads, cost


def optimise(X, y, beta, beta_0, num_iterations=1000, learning_rate=0.005, print_cost=False):
    costs = []
    for i in range(num_iterations):

        # calculate cost and gradients
        grads, cost = propagate(X, y, beta, beta_0)

        # retrieve derivatives from grads
        dbeta = grads["dbeta"]
        dbeta_0 = grads["dbeta_0"]

        # updating procedure
        beta = beta - learning_rate * dbeta 
        beta_0 = beta_0 - learning_rate * dbeta_0 

        if i % 100 == 0:
            costs.append(cost) # append the cost
      
        # print the cost every 100 iterations
        if print_cost and i % 100 == 0:
            print ("cost after iteration %i: %f" %(i, cost))
  
    # save parameters and gradients in dictionary
    params = {"beta": beta, "beta_0": beta_0}
    grads = {"dbeta": dbeta, "dbeta_0": dbeta_0}
  
    return params, grads, costs
In [15]:
# function to predict the classification labels 
def predict(X_test, beta, beta_0, decision_threshold):
  n = X_test.shape[1]
  y_pred = np.zeros((1,n))
  beta = beta.reshape(X_test.shape[0], 1)
  
  # compute vector y_log predicting the probabilities
  y_log = predict_log(X_test, beta, beta_0)
  
  for i in range(y_log.shape[1]):
      # convert probabilities y_log to actual predictions y_pred
      if y_log[0, i] > decision_threshold:
          y_pred[0, i] = 1
      else:
          y_pred[0, i] = 0
  
  assert(y_pred.shape==(1, n))
  return y_pred


# define model
def model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, decision_threshold, learning_rate, num_iterations=2000, print_cost=False, print_acc=False):
  # initialize parameters with zeros
  beta, beta_0 = initialise(X_train.shape[0])

  # gradient descent
  parameters, grads, costs = optimise(X_train, y_train, beta, beta_0, num_iterations, learning_rate, print_cost=print_cost)

  # retrieve parameters beta and beta_0 from dictionary "parameters"
  beta = parameters["beta"]
  beta_0 = parameters["beta_0"]

  # predict test and train set examples
  y_pred_test = predict(X_test, beta, beta_0, decision_threshold)
  y_pred_train = predict(X_train, beta, beta_0, decision_threshold)
  
  # print train/test Errors
  train_acc = 100 - np.mean(np.abs(y_pred_train - y_train)) * 100
  test_acc = 100 - np.mean(np.abs(y_pred_test - y_test)) * 100
  if print_acc:
    print("train accuracy: {} %".format(train_acc))
    print("test accuracy: {} %".format(test_acc))

  # saving all information
  d = {"costs": costs, "y_pred_test": y_pred_test, "y_pred_train": y_pred_train, "beta": beta, "beta_0": beta_0, "learning_rate": learning_rate, "num_iterations": num_iterations, "train_acc": train_acc, "test_acc": test_acc}
  
  return d

Investigate the sensitivity of the model to slight variations in the decision threshold and learning rate.

Get ready for a 5-fold cross validation: split the datasets in folds

In [18]:
def cross_val_evaluate(data, num_folds, decision_threshold, learning_rate):

    folds = cross_val_split(data, num_folds)  # we get transposed folds, data is (800, 11) dimensional

    train_accs = []
    val_accs = []

    for i in range(len(folds)):
        print('Fold', i+1)
        # define the training set
        train_set = np.delete(np.asarray(folds).reshape(len(folds), folds[0].shape[0], folds[0].shape[1]), i, axis=0)
        train_folds = train_set.reshape(len(train_set)*train_set[0].shape[0], train_set[0].shape[1])

        X_train = train_folds[:,:-1].T  # transpose the data to use logistic regression
        y_train = train_folds[:,-1].T

        # define the validation set
        val_fold = folds[i]
        X_val = val_fold[:,:-1].T
        y_val = val_fold[:,-1].T

        # train the model
        d = model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, decision_threshold, learning_rate, num_iterations=5000, print_acc=True)

        # evaluate
        train_acc = d["train_acc"]
        val_acc = d["test_acc"]

        train_accs.append(train_acc)
        val_accs.append(val_acc)

    return train_accs, val_accs

We now turn to the hyperparameters - learning_rate and decision_threshold, and build a 5x5 hyperparameter grid to find their optimal values based on the accuracy of their predictions.

The learning rate determines how fast we converge to the desired values; if it is too small, we will need too many iterations to converge to the desired values. The decision threshold is the probability threshold at which we assign 1 to the prediction, essentially, if the probability y_log is above the decision threshold, the preciction is 1.

Now, define a function grid() where we perform a grid search through the candidate hyperparameters. It is a double for loop, where at each iteration we save the accuracies and the two parameters used to get that accuracy in three separate lists, recording their indices. When done looping over the parameters, we find the index of the largest accuracy and then look up the (optimal) parameters used to get that maximum accuracy.

In [25]:
# define a 5x5 hyperparameter grid 
learning_rates = [0.001,0.003,0.005,0.007,0.1]
dec_thresholds = [0.35,0.4,0.45,0.5,0.6]

# take the validation accuracy as the metric
def grid(data_train):
    list_lr = []
    list_dt = []
    list_accuracy = []
    
    for i in learning_rates:
        print('\nLearning rate',i)
        list_lr_row = []
        list_dt_row = []
        list_accuracy_row = []
        for j in dec_thresholds:
            print('Decision threshold',j)
            # returns lists of training and validation accuracies
            train_accs, val_accs = cross_val_evaluate(data_train, 5, j, i) # 5 is the number of folds
            # get average over the 5 folds
            val_acc = np.mean(val_accs)
            list_lr_row.append(i)
            list_dt_row.append(j)
            list_accuracy_row.append(val_acc)
        list_lr.append(list_lr_row)
        list_dt.append(list_dt_row)
        list_accuracy.append(list_accuracy_row)

    list_lr=np.array(list_lr)
    list_dt=np.array(list_dt)
    list_accuracy=np.array(list_accuracy)
    
    max_acc = np.max(list_accuracy)
    index_max_acc = np.argwhere(list_accuracy == np.max(list_accuracy))[0]
    print('Maximum validation accuracy: %f' %(max_acc))
    print('Optimal learning value: %f' %(list_lr[index_max_acc[0],index_max_acc[1]]))
    print('Optimal decision threshold: %f' %(list_dt[index_max_acc[0],index_max_acc[1]]))
    return list_lr,list_dt,list_accuracy

It is very slow, grid search which is a brute-force method which is not the best way to search for optimal parameters.

Now investigate how the cost decreases for different learning rates as we go through the iterations with our fixed decision threshold, this is to see how fast the convergence is.

In [29]:
# candidate learning rates
learning_rates = [0.001,0.003,0.005,0.007,0.01]
models = []

for i in learning_rates:
    d = model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, 0.5, i, num_iterations=5000, print_cost=False)
    models.append(d)
for i in range(len(learning_rates)):
    plt.plot(np.squeeze(models[i]['costs']),label=str(models[i]['learning_rate']))
plt.ylabel('cost')
plt.xlabel('number of iterations in hundreds')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Notice that we get the best accuracy results for learning rate 0.005. We see that it is among the faster convergent learning rates. Note that merely looking at the cost is not enough because if we choose the cost too low, there is a danger of overfitting. And with a very small learning rate we see that the cost is higher, convergence is not as fast and we are in danger of having a model that is too general and has high variance.

In the next subsection, we will check the difference between the train and test accuracies - we will see that the model is overfitting if the train accuracy is higher than the test accuracy. This will justify and guide our choice of the optimal parameters.

2.1.2.¶

We now compare the performance of the optimal model on the training data and on the test data by their mean accuracies.

Varying the parameters a bit and comparing the accuracies we get, we see that the model is more sensitive to changes in decision threshold rather than learning rate.

# standardize the X_train and X_test
def standardise(X):
    mu = np.mean(X, 0)
    sigma = np.std(X, 0)
    X_std = (X - mu) / sigma
    return X_std
In [69]:

In [75]:
# define cross-entropy loss function to account for information gain
def entropy(y, sample_weights=None):
  if sample_weights is None:
      sample_weights = np.ones(y.shape[0]) / y.shape[0]
  
  entropy = 0
  num = y.shape[0]  # number of labels
  label_counts = {}  # calculate different labels in yand store in label_counts
  for i in range(num):
      if y[i] not in label_counts.keys():
          label_counts[y[i]] = 0
      label_counts[y[i]] += sample_weights[i]
  
  for key in label_counts:
      prob = float(label_counts[key]) / float(np.sum(sample_weights))
      entropy -= prob*math.log2(prob)

  return entropy
In [76]:
# check if we get a reasonable value for the entropy

We have prepared the data and defined entropy, now define the functions for the random forest implementation.

In [77]:
def split_dataset(X, y, column, value, sample_weights=None):
  ret = []
  featVec = X[:, column]
  X = X[:,[i for i in range(X.shape[1]) if i!=column]]
  
  for i in range(len(featVec)):
      if featVec[i]==value:
          ret.append(i)
  
  sub_X = X[ret,:]
  sub_y = y[ret]
  sub_sample_weights = sample_weights[ret]

  return sub_X, sub_y, sub_sample_weights
In [78]:
def entropy_purification(X, y, column, sample_weights=None):
  if sample_weights is None:
      sample_weights = np.ones(y.shape[0]) / y.shape[0]
  
  new_entropy = 0
  old_cost = entropy(y, sample_weights)
  
  unique_vals = np.unique(X[:, column])

  new_cost = 0.0
  #split the values of i-th feature and calculate the cost 
  for value in unique_vals:
      sub_X, sub_y, sub_sample_weights = split_dataset(X, y, column, value, sample_weights)
      prob = np.sum(sub_sample_weights) / float(np.sum(sample_weights))
      new_cost += prob * entropy(sub_y, sub_sample_weights)
  
  new_entropy = old_cost - new_cost # information gain

  return new_entropy
In [79]:
# evaluate for feature 2
entropy_purification(X_train, y_train, 2)

Function that determines the best feature to split by:

In [80]:
def choose_best_feature(X, y,n_features, sample_weights=None):
  if sample_weights is None:
      sample_weights = np.ones(y.shape[0]) / y.shape[0]

  best_feature_idx = 0
#   n_features = X.shape[1]    
  
  # use C4.5 algorirhm
  best_gain_cost = 0.0
  for i in range(n_features):
      info_gain_cost = entropy_purification(X, y, i, sample_weights)        
      if info_gain_cost > best_gain_cost:
          best_gain_cost = info_gain_cost
          best_feature_idx = i                

  return best_feature_idx

Number of unique values in column 0 is 30

Number of unique values in column 5 is 4
Number of unique values in column 6 is 4
Number of unique values in column 7 is 49
Number of unique values in column 8 is 4
Number of unique values in column 9 is 2

Notice that in column 2 we have an unreasonably large number of unique values. The algorithm chooses the descriptoor with the most features as it gives the most information - the cross entropy is expected to have the largest value for column 2. As we choose column 2, very time there is an unique value, we get a new subtree and do not use the full possible depth. This will make the random forest memorise our data and overfit.

Check the cross entropy values:

We clearly see that the entropy which guides the choice in determining the best feature to split by is dependent on the unique values in the column. A way around this is to remove columns 2, 0 and 7 later to see whether we get better results for the random forest.

Majority vote function that gives us the classification label (in out case 0 or 1) that is most common in y:

In [84]:
def majority_vote(y, sample_weights=None):
  if sample_weights is None:
      sample_weights = np.ones(y.shape[0]) / y.shape[0]
  
  majority_label = y[0]

  dict_num = {}
  for i in range(y.shape[0]):
      if y[i] not in dict_num.keys():
          dict_num[y[i]] = sample_weights[i]
      else:
          dict_num[y[i]] += sample_weights[i]
  
  majority_label = max(dict_num, key=dict_num.get)

  return majority_label
In [85]:
majority_vote(y_train)
Out[85]:
1.0

Define the decision tree building and training functions:

In [86]:
def build_tree(X, y, n_features, feature_names, depth, sample_weights=None, max_depth=10, min_samples_leaf=2):
    mytree = dict()
    # include a clause for the cases where (i) no feature, (ii) all labels are the same, (iii) depth exceed, or (iv) X is too small
    if len(feature_names)==0 or len(np.unique(y))==1 or depth>=max_depth or len(X)<=min_samples_leaf: 
        return majority_vote(y, sample_weights)

    else:
        best_feature_idx = choose_best_feature(X, y, n_features, sample_weights)
        best_feature_name = feature_names[best_feature_idx]
        feature_names = feature_names[:]
        feature_names.remove(best_feature_name)

    mytree = {best_feature_name:{}}
    
    unique_vals = np.unique(X[:, best_feature_idx])
    
    for value in unique_vals:
        sub_X, sub_y, sub_sample_weights = split_dataset(X, y, best_feature_idx, value, sample_weights) 
        mytree[best_feature_name][value] = build_tree(sub_X, sub_y, n_features, feature_names, depth+1, sub_sample_weights)

    return mytree
In [87]:
def train(X, y, n_features, depth, sample_weights=None):
  """
  Build the decision tree according to the training data.
  Args:
      X: (pd.Dataframe) training features, of shape (N, D). Each X[i] is a training sample.
      y: (pd.Series) vector of training labels, of shape (N,). y[i] is the label for X[i], and each y[i] is
      an integer in the range 0 <= y[i] <= C. Here C = 1.
      sample_weights: weights for each samples, of shape (N,).
  """
  if sample_weights is None:
      # if the sample weights is not provided, we assume the samples have uniform weights
      sample_weights = np.ones(X.shape[0]) / X.shape[0]
  else:
      sample_weights = np.array(sample_weights) / np.sum(sample_weights)

  feature_names = X.columns.tolist()
  X = np.array(X)
  y = np.array(y)
  tree = build_tree(X, y,n_features, feature_names, depth, sample_weights=sample_weights)
  return tree

In [90]:
def classify(tree, x):  # classify one element of y_pred with the fitted decision tree
  feature_name = list(tree.keys())[0]  # select first element of the tree dict - the feature name
  second_dict = tree[feature_name]            
  key = x.loc[feature_name]
  if key not in second_dict:
      key = np.random.choice(list(second_dict.keys()))
  value_of_key = second_dict[key]
  if isinstance(value_of_key, dict):
      label = classify(value_of_key, x)
  else:
      label=value_of_key
  return label

Finally, this function outputs a numpy array of the classification prediction using the above classification function that classifies each 'row' (element of y_pred) using the decision tree we trained.

In [91]:
def predict(X, y, tree):
    if len(X.shape)==1:
        return classify(tree, X)
    else:
        results=[]
        for i in range(X.shape[0]):
            results.append(classify(tree, X.iloc[i, :]))
        return np.array(results)
In [92]:
def score(X_test, y_test, tree, depth):
    y_pred = predict(X_test, y_test, tree)  # X_test and y_test are pandas dataframes
    return np.float(sum(y_pred==y_test)) / float(len(y_test)), y_pred
In [93]:

test_acc, test_y_pred = score(X_2, y_2, tree3, depth)
print('Training accuracy:', tr_acc)

Training accuracy: 0.9975
Test accuracy: 0.54

The model with default hyperparameters depth = 5, n_features = 5 has clearly overfitted the data because the training accuracy is very high and the test accuracy is much lower (nearly half of the train one). This may be due to the large number of unique values in the predictors.

Now we look for the optimal parameters:

1) number of decision trees: used in the random forest implementation

2) depth of trees: used in build_tree()

3) max number of descriptors (features) randomly chosen at each split: used in choose_best_feature()

Now that we have defined the functions to get a decision tree, we will perform a 5-fold cross validation to find the optimal parameters: we will run 5 models on different folds and judge the performance by the accuracy of the predictions.

In [94]:
def score2(y_pred, y_test):
    return np.float(sum(y_pred==y_test)) / float(len(y_test)), y_pred  # accuracy of predictions

# data and data_test are np.arrays
def cross_val_evaluate_RF(data, data_test, num_folds, n_features, n_trees=5, depth=1,print_accs=True):
  
    folds = cross_val_split(data, num_folds) # split data into folds
    
    # convert and split the test data into X_test and y_tests
    data_test = pd.DataFrame(data_test)
    X_test = data_test.iloc[:,:-1]
    y_test = data_test.iloc[:,-1]
    
    # initialise lists to contain the accuracies
    train_accs = []
    val_accs = []
    test_accs = []
    
    VAL_ACC = []
    TEST_ACC = []
    
    # initialise the list to contain the prediction for the five folds
    y_preds_val_fold = []
    y_preds_test_fold = []
    
    if print_accs:
        print('\n\ndepth',depth)
        print('nb of trees',n_trees)
        print('nb of features',n_features)
        
    for i in range(len(folds)):
        if print_accs:
            print('\nfold',i+1)
        # define the training set
        train_set = np.delete(np.asarray(folds).reshape(len(folds), folds[0].shape[0], folds[0].shape[1]), i, axis=0)
        train_folds = train_set.reshape(len(train_set)*train_set[0].shape[0], train_set[0].shape[1])
    
        # define the validation set
        val_fold = folds[i]

        # convert to dataframes
        train_folds = pd.DataFrame(train_folds) # train
        val_fold = pd.DataFrame(val_fold) # validation 

        # get the lists for average accuracies for the forests
        avg_train_accs = []
        avg_val_accs = []
        avg_test_accs = []
        
        y_trains_forest = []
        y_val_forest = []
        y_test_forest = []
        
        
        # loop through the forest
        for n in range(n_trees):
            sample_tr = train_folds.sample(n=train_folds.shape[0], replace=True, random_state=n)  # change the random state to have different sampling for each tree
            X_tr1 = sample_tr.iloc[:,:-1]
            y_tr1 = sample_tr.iloc[:,-1]

#             sample_val = val_fold.sample(n=val_fold.shape[0], replace=True, random_state=1)
            X_tr2 = val_fold.iloc[:,:-1]
            y_tr2 = val_fold.iloc[:,-1]
            
            # create the tree with this set of parameters and sampled training set
            tree = train(X_tr1, y_tr1, n_features, depth)

            # get the accuracy and prediction for each individual tree
            train_acc, tr_y_pred = score(X_tr1, y_tr1, tree, depth)  # we need to input the training set, the testing set and the hyperparameters 
            avg_train_accs.append(train_acc)

            val_acc, val_y_pred = score(X_tr2, y_tr2, tree, depth)
            avg_val_accs.append(val_acc)
            
            test_acc, test_y_pred = score(X_test, y_test, tree, depth)
            avg_test_accs.append(test_acc)
            
            # append the y_preds
            y_trains_forest.append(tr_y_pred)
            y_val_forest.append(val_y_pred)
            y_test_forest.append(test_y_pred)
        
        
        # append the average of the validation and test accuracies over the individual trees
        VAL_ACC.append(np.average(avg_val_accs))
        TEST_ACC.append(np.average(avg_test_accs))
            
        # sum the predictions of the trees over the forest
        y_tr_sum_forest = [sum(i) for i in zip(*y_trains_forest)]
        y_val_sum_forest = [sum(i) for i in zip(*y_val_forest)]
        y_test_sum_forest = [sum(i) for i in zip(*y_test_forest)]
        
        # divide by the number of trees
        y_tr_sum_forest = [i/n_trees for i in y_tr_sum_forest]
        y_val_sum_forest = [i/n_trees for i in y_val_sum_forest]
        y_test_sum_forest = [i/n_trees for i in y_test_sum_forest]
        
        # set to 1 if above 0.5 set to 0 if below 0.5, set the case for 0.5 to equal 0 to avoid false positives
        for k in range(len(y_tr_sum_forest)):
            if y_tr_sum_forest[k]>0.5:
                y_tr_sum_forest[k]=1
            else:
                y_tr_sum_forest[k]=0
        
        for k in range(len(y_val_sum_forest)):  # this is our y_pred over the validation fold
            if y_val_sum_forest[k]>0.5:
                y_val_sum_forest[k]=1
            else:
                y_val_sum_forest[k]=0
        
        for k in range(len(y_test_sum_forest)):  # this is our y_pred over the validation fold
            if y_test_sum_forest[k]>0.5:
                y_test_sum_forest[k]=1
            else:
                y_test_sum_forest[k]=0
                
        # we now have the prediction for this forest, calculate the score for this fold:
        score12,_ = score2(y_tr_sum_forest, y_tr1)
        score1,_ = score2(y_val_sum_forest, y_tr2)
        score_test,_ = score2(y_test_sum_forest, y_test)
        if print_accs:
            print('accuracy, training set, fold',i+1,'is',score12)
            print('accuracy, validation set, fold',i+1,'is',score1)
            print('accuracy, test set, fold',i+1,'is',score_test)
        
        # append the scores for each fold
        train_accs.append(score12)
        val_accs.append(score1)
        test_accs.append(score_test)

        
        # append the y_pred validation for each fold
        y_preds_val_fold.append(y_val_sum_forest)
        y_preds_test_fold.append(y_test_sum_forest)

    return train_accs, val_accs, test_accs, y_preds_val_fold, y_preds_test_fold, VAL_ACC, TEST_ACC

Having a lowest testing accuracy on unseen data seems reasonable, and printing out the predictions for y_test shows that we do not get predictions of the same class at all times.

Note that in what follows we take the metric as the validation and testing accuracy of the final y_pred averaged over the five folds. We will then compare this metric in determining the optimal hyperparameters based on the average of the accuracies over the individual trees.

The acccuracies on the training set are larger than on the test set, this is expected, so we continue by scanning through the optimal parameters separately.

i) Investigate the accuracies over different depths with other hyperparameters set to constant values.

ii) Scanning through the number of trees to get an intuition, choose depth = 3, based on the maximum accuracy achieved on the training set previously.

We see that the accuracy plateau is at around 25, so we take this as the optimal value; ideally it would be larger for marginally better accuracies but we have serious computational power constraints. A larger number of trees is more optimal as there is more averaging out of outtlier accuracies.

The maximum depth is one of the stopping criteria for the algorithm - it sets a maximum number of splits in the decision tree.

iii) Now investigate the optimal number of features randomly chosen at each split, note that we cannot go above 9 because there are 10 training features overall. Choose optimal n_trees = 25 and depth = 3.

In [260]:
max_acc_val = 0
max_acc_test = 0
list_params_val = [0,0,0]  # [tree, n_features, depths]
list_params_test = [0,0,0] 
for tr in nbs_trees:
    print('\nLoading for',tr,'trees...')
    for feat in nbs_feat:
        print('Loading for',feat,'features...')
        for d in depths:
            _,val_accs,test_accs,_,_ = cross_val_evaluate_RF(arr_train1, arr_test1, 5, n_features=feat, n_trees=tr, depth=d,print_accs=False)
            acc_new_val = np.average(val_accs)
            if acc_new_val>max_acc_val:
                max_acc_val = acc_new_val
                list_params_val = [tr,feat,d]
                
            acc_new_test = np.average(test_accs)
            print('depth',d,'average testing accuracy',acc_new_test)
            if acc_new_test>max_acc_test:
                max_acc_test = acc_new_test
                list_params_test = [tr,feat,d]
                
print('max_acc_val',max_acc_val)
print(list_params_val)

print('max_acc_test',max_acc_test)
print(list_params_test)

alternative accuracy aggregation¶

We now take the metric of determining the hyperparameters based on the accuracies calculated for the prediction of each individual tree, averaged out in the number of trees in the forest, which is then averaged out over the five folds. We do this both for the validation and test sets.

In [100]:

print('candidate depths',depths)

In [104]:
max_acc_val = 0
max_acc_test = 0
list_params_val = [0,0,0]  # [tree, n_features, depths]
list_params_test = [0,0,0] 
for tr in nbs_trees:
    print('\nLoading for',tr,'trees...')
    for feat in nbs_feat:
        print('Loading for',feat,'features...')
        for d in depths:
            _,_,_,_,_,val_accs,test_accs = cross_val_evaluate_RF(arr_train1, arr_test1, 5, n_features=feat, n_trees=tr, depth=d, print_accs=False)
            acc_new_val = np.average(val_accs)
            if acc_new_val>max_acc_val:
                max_acc_val = acc_new_val
                list_params_val = [tr,feat,d]
                
            acc_new_test = np.average(test_accs)
            print('depth',d,'average testing accuracy',acc_new_test)  # print out the most important metric
            if acc_new_test>max_acc_test:
                max_acc_test = acc_new_test
                list_params_test = [tr,feat,d]

This method of calculating the accuracies is not the best as it gives the optimal number of trees as the smallest one, while it is expected that the accuracy goes up as the number of trees increases.

Recall that the most important metric is the testing accuracy, but it is also important to see the accuracies on the training set to have a reasonable qualitative intuition about overfitting the training data, balancing out the generalisation to the testing data.

We therefore take the optimal hyperparameters based on the accuracies calculated using the first method, and those computed on the testing set: 30 trees, 5 features and depth 2.

Now remove columns 0 and 2 where we have a lot of unique values which makes the tree always to predict based on that value. The small optimal depth also makes sense as trees never really goes into depth after we have a number of features larger than 3. Then we will perform the grid search for that and compare the accuracy we get in the next subsection.

In [37]:
def confusion_matrix(y_actual,y_pred,print_info=True):
    assert(len(y_actual)==len(y_pred))
    tp = 0
    fp = 0
    tn = 0
    fn = 0
    n = len(y_actual)
    for i in range(n):
        if y_actual[i]==1 and y_pred[i]==1: tp += 1
        if y_actual[i]==0 and y_pred[i]==1: fp += 1
        if y_actual[i]==0 and y_pred[i]==0: tn += 1
        if y_actual[i]==1 and y_pred[i]==0: fn += 1
    if print_info:
        print('TP:',tp,'FP:', fp,'TN:', tn,'FN:', fn)
    return tp, fp, tn, fn

Define a function to train our data using an optimal random forest:

In [165]:
# iterate through the trees in the forest:
    
def eval_forest(data_train, data_test, n_trees, n_features, depth):

    y_trains_forest = []
    y_val_forest = []
        
    for n in range(n_trees):
        sample_tr = data_train.sample(n=data_train.shape[0], replace=True, random_state=n)
        X_tr1 = sample_tr.iloc[:,:-1]
        y_tr1 = sample_tr.iloc[:,-1]
        X_tr2 = data_test.iloc[:,:-1]
        y_tr2 = data_test.iloc[:,-1]

        # create the tree with this set of parameters and sampled training set
        tree = train(X_tr1, y_tr1, n_features, depth)

        # get the accuracy and prediction for each individual tree
        tr_y_pred = predict(X_tr1, y_tr1, tree)  # we need to input the training set, the testing set and the hyperparameters 
        val_y_pred = predict(X_tr2, y_tr2, tree)

        # call the predict function, append the y_preds
        y_trains_forest.append(tr_y_pred)
        y_val_forest.append(val_y_pred)
            
    # sum the predictions of the trees over the forest
    y_tr_sum_forest = [sum(i) for i in zip(*y_trains_forest)]
    y_val_sum_forest = [sum(i) for i in zip(*y_val_forest)]

    # divide by the number of trees
    y_tr_forest = [i/n_trees for i in y_tr_sum_forest]
    y_val_forest = [i/n_trees for i in y_val_sum_forest]

    # set to 1 if above 0.5 set to 0 if below 0.5, set the case for 0.5 to equal 0 to avoid false positives
    for k in range(len(y_tr_forest)):
        if y_tr_forest[k]>0.5:
            y_tr_forest[k]=1
        else:
            y_tr_forest[k]=0

    for k in range(len(y_val_forest)):  # this is our y_pred over the validation fold
        if y_val_forest[k]>0.5:
            y_val_forest[k]=1
        else:
            y_val_forest[k]=0
            
    return y_tr_forest, y_val_forest

An alternative to the current approach would be modifying the building of the tree from the ground to change the branching pattern that arises in this case due to the high number of unique values in some of the columns.

2.3. SVMs¶

We define the hinge loss as $$ \mathcal L (\boldsymbol w) = \frac{1}{2} \| \boldsymbol w \|^2 + \frac{\lambda}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \max \bigg( 0, 1-y_i (\boldsymbol w \cdot x_i + b) \bigg) \, . $$ where $\boldsymbol w$ is the vector of weights that defines the hyperplane, $\lambda$ is the regularisation parameter, and $b$ the intercept which is included in X_train as the additional last column of $1$'s.

Note about the interpretation of the margin: in the notebooks, we were given an algorithm that can work (roughly) for both types of margins, depending on the regularisation parameter $\lambda$ that is set. If we set it to a very large value, we recover the hard margin as errors are penalised harshly, while a very small $\lambda$ allows for a tight fit that may be too specific to the training data. This parameter essentially allows us to control the tradeoff between the complexity of the model (too complex and specific leads to overfitting) and minimising training errors (accuracy).

The considerations whether the data is linearly separable are crucial here - data that is non-linearly separable will not be fit well using any hard-margin approach using a large value for $\lambda$.

Also, we use the maximum function to account for the fact that we only take into account the values that satisfy the constraint, otherwise they do not contribute to the definition of the hyperplane that separates the data and is essentially the model.

2.3.1.¶

We now write the functions to implement the standard linear hard-margin SVM.

In [280]:
# define function to calculate hinge loss
def compute_cost(W, X, y, regul_strength=1e5):
    n = X.shape[0]
    distances = 1 - y * (np.dot(X, W))  
    distances[distances < 0] = 0  # equivalent to max(0, distance)
    hinge = regul_strength * (np.sum(distances) / n) 

    # calculate cost
    cost = 1 / 2 * np.dot(W, W) + hinge
    return cost
In [281]:
# calculate gradient of cost
def calculate_cost_gradient(W, X_batch, y_batch, regul_strength=1e5):
    # if only one example is passed
    if type(y_batch) == np.float64:
        y_batch = np.asarray([y_batch])
        X_batch = np.asarray([X_batch])  # gives multidimensional array
  
    distance = 1 - (y_batch * np.dot(X_batch, W))
    dw = np.zeros(len(W))

    for ind, d in enumerate(distance):
        if max(0, d)==0:
            di = W
        else:
            di = W - (regul_strength * y_batch[ind] * X_batch[ind])
        dw += di

    dw = dw/len(y_batch)  # average
    return dw
In [282]:
def sgd(X, y, max_iterations=2000, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-5, regul_strength=1e5, print_outcome=False):
  # write the initial conditions for the weights
  weights = np.ones(X.shape[1])
  nth = 0
  # initialise starting cost as infinity
  prev_cost = np.inf
  
  # stochastic gradient descent
  for iteration in range(1, max_iterations):
      # shuffle to prevent repeating update cycles
      np.random.shuffle([X, y])
      for ind, x in enumerate(X):
          ascent = calculate_cost_gradient(weights, x, y[ind], regul_strength)
          weights = weights - (learning_rate * ascent)

      # convergence check on 2^n'th iteration
      if iteration==2**nth or iteration==max_iterations-1:
          # compute cost
          cost = compute_cost(weights, X, y, regul_strength) 
          if print_outcome:
            print("Iteration is: {}, Cost is: {}".format(iteration, cost))
          # stop criterion
          if abs(prev_cost - cost) < stop_criterion * prev_cost:
              return weights
          
          prev_cost = cost
          nth += 1
  
  return weights

To implement the hard margin, we only need to find the minimal $\textbf{w}$ such that $\frac{1}{2}||\textbf{w}||^2$. But as mentioned before, this is recovered when we set the regul_param to infinity (analytically). Also, if we initialise the weights to a vector of ones, we get slightly better results, but they are strongly dependent on the initial conditions.

Having defined the functions that accommodate the soft margin, we can recover the hard margin by setting the regularisation strength to a very large value; we set $\lambda=10^5$ and hope this is large enough computationally. Recall that this means that the outliers will be penalised harshly; it also means that the model will not work well for data that is not linearly separable.

In [283]:

print("Training finished.")

Evaluate the mean accuracies:

In [285]:
def score(W, X, y):
    y_preds = np.array([])
    for i in range(X.shape[0]):
        y_pred = np.sign(np.dot(X[i], W))
        y_preds = np.append(y_preds, y_pred)
    return np.float(sum(y_preds==y)) / float(len(y))
In [286]:

print("Accuracy on test set: {}".format(score(W, X_2.to_numpy(), y_2.to_numpy())))

Define a separate function to get the predictio for the linear hard-margin SVM. We are predicting by projecting (with the dot product) the location of each x relative to the hyperplane W defined by the support vectors - if it is 'below' the hyperplane, we get a negative sign, if it is 'above', a positive sign.

In [287]:
def predict_linSVM(W, X, y):
    y_preds = np.array([])
    for i in range(X.shape[0]):
        y_pred = np.sign(np.dot(X[i], W)) 
        y_preds = np.append(y_preds, y_pred)
    return y_preds

Now implement the calculation of the F1 score:

In [493]:
def confusion_matrix(y_actual,y_pred,print_info=True):
    assert(len(y_actual)==len(y_pred))
    tp = 0
    fp = 0
    tn = 0
    fn = 0
    n = len(y_actual)
    for i in range(n):
        if y_actual[i]==1 and y_pred[i]==1: tp += 1
        if y_actual[i]==-1 and y_pred[i]==1: fp += 1
        if y_actual[i]==-1 and y_pred[i]==-1: tn += 1
        if y_actual[i]==1 and y_pred[i]==-1: fn += 1
    if print_info:
        print('TP:',tp,'FP:', fp,'TN:', tn,'FN:', fn)
    return tp, fp, tn, fn

def prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn):
    precision = 0
    recall = 0
    if tp+fp != 0:
        precision = tp/(tp+fp)
    if tp+fn != 0:
        recall = tp/(tp+fn)
    return precision, recall
        
def f1_score(precision, recall, print_info=True):
    if precision==0 or recall==0:
        f1 = 0
    else:
        f1 = 2*(precision*recall)/(precision+recall)
    if print_info:
        print('F1 score :',f1)
    return f1

y_actual = y_1.to_numpy()

print('Recall :', recall)  # sensitivity

The scores for the hard-margin linear SVM are not too bad for both training and testing sets, the model seems to generalise well to unseen testing data as the difference between training and testing scores is not very significant.

As an extension, we investgate the optimal regularisation strength to judge whether the hard or soft margin works better with our data and how well it generalises. This will also make it easier to make inferences about how the kernelised SVM works based on the distribution of the data we will observe now. To do that, we do a grid search for the hyperparameter regul_strength in a 5-fold CV.

In [293]:
def cross_val_evaluate(data, data_test, num_folds,reg_str):
  
  folds = cross_val_split(data, num_folds)  # we get transposed folds, data is (800, 11) dimensional

  F1_scores = [] # for score on validation folds
  F1_train = [] # on training fold
  F1_test = [] # on test set (most important one)

  for i in range(len(folds)):
    print('Fold', i+1)
    # define the training set
    train_set = np.delete(np.asarray(folds).reshape(len(folds), folds[0].shape[0], folds[0].shape[1]), i, axis=0)
    train_folds = train_set.reshape(len(train_set)*train_set[0].shape[0], train_set[0].shape[1])
    
    X_train = train_folds[:,:-1]
    y_train = train_folds[:,-1]
    
    # define the validation set
    val_fold = folds[i]
    X_val = val_fold[:,:-1]
    y_val = val_fold[:,-1]
    
    X_test = data_test[:,:-1]
    y_test = data_test[:,-1]

    # train the model
    W = sgd(X_train, y_train, max_iterations=1500, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-3, regul_strength=reg_str, print_outcome=True)
    
    y_pred_train = predict_linSVM(W,X_train,y_train)  # get y_pred on training fold
    y_pred_val = predict_linSVM(W,X_val,y_val)  # get y_pred on validation fold
    y_pred_test = predict_linSVM(W,X_test,y_test)  # get y_pred on unseen test set
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the train fold
    tp, fp, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_train,y_pred_train)
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    F1_tr = f1_score(precision, recall)
    F1_train.append(F1_tr)
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the validation fold
    tp, fp, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_val,y_pred_val)
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    F1 = f1_score(precision, recall)
    F1_scores.append(F1)
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the test set
    tp, fp, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred_test)
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    F1_t = f1_score(precision, recall)
    F1_test.append(F1_t)

  return F1_scores, F1_train, F1_test
In [294]:
# we have our training data in dataframes X_1 and y_1, stack them into a numpy
X_1=X_1.to_numpy()
y_1=y_1.to_numpy()
y_1 = (np.zeros((1,800))+y_1).T
X_2=X_2.to_numpy()
y_2=y_2.to_numpy()
y_2 = (np.zeros((1,200))+y_2).T
# stack the X and y train together so that permutation does not violate the correspondence of the predictors and outcome
data_train = np.hstack((X_1,y_1))  
data_test = np.hstack((X_2,y_2))

We now investigate the performance of the linear SVM when we vary the regularisation parameter, which quantifies the importance the errors (misclassifications) in the model. It will also give a glimpse into how linearly separable out data is - recall that for small values of $\lambda$ we have a soft margin, and for large values we recover the hard margin.

In [75]:
reg_strs = [2,20,100,250,500,1e3,1e5,1e8]
scan_val = []
scan_train = []
scan_test = []
for rs in reg_strs:
    F1_scores, F1_tr, F1_test = cross_val_evaluate(data_train, data_test, 5, rs)
    scan_val.append(np.average(F1_scores))
    scan_train.append(np.average(F1_tr))
    scan_test.append(np.average(F1_test))

We clearly see from the quality of the predictions based on the F1 score that the model performs best with a small regularisation strength, 2 and 20 being the best on both training (validation folds) and unseen test datasets. This suggests that a linear hard margin SVM (with high regularisation strength) may not be the best way to build a model for this kind of high-dimensional dataset.

Before trying the soft-margin SVM, another method to tackle is to find a suitable kernel that will project our data points into an extra dimension and attempt to define a hyperplane that separates them in that space. Importantly, this extra dimension is defined solely using the values of the original dimensions, so we must be careful about defining it so that it suits well our dataset and, importantly, future datasets. This is done by taking advantage of the data values in the lower conditions and 'express' some properties that differentiate the +1 and -1 predictions which in turn allows to define a good hyperplane that separates the data well.

ii) Radial Basis Function kernel SVM¶

We now implement the hard margin non-linear kernel SVM with radial basis function (RBF) kernel and do a grid search to find the optimal hyperparameter. To keep the margin hard, we penalise the misclassifications (unreasonably) harshly and keep the regularisation parameter very high, $\lambda = 10^5$. The kernel allows to compute an extra dimension of the data, thus adding an extra dimension to the hyperplane that will separate it. The choice of the kernel is crucial here, especially with high-dimensional datta as it needs to take advantage of the existing coordinates to make their properties more 'expressed'. If the Gaussian kernel is suitable, we should expect a better performance than the linear SVM, but this is not necessarily the case if the data is not clustered nicely even with the extra dimension.

There are some crucial changes in the computation of the predictions. We first replace the dot product operations with the kernel function. Also, we do not have the weights as in the linear case because we are defining the hyper-plane in higher dimensions by using the kernel. This means that the weights in the kernelised SVM are not as directly related to the input space.

We will use the coefficients $\alpha$ to compute the predictions. We will also need compute the hyperplane bias $b$ explicitly and not 'on the fly' as the last entry of W, as we did it for the linear case. This is becausee it is not involved in the kernel multiplication.

Moreover, using the kernel trick makes thee optimisation problem dual - therefore we need more advanced optimisation such as quadratic programming or linear programming with inequalities to solve this problem. This is because when we switch to the kernelised SVM, we optimise over the space of the number of data points (rows), while in the linear SVM we only need to optimise over the (much smaller) space of the number of features (columns).

Now compute the radial basis kernel with the hyperparameter $\sigma$ (default is 0.5) that we will need to optimise using the five-fold cross-validation. Note that we need to optimise to avoid overfitting which happens for small values of $\sigma$. (Source: "Kernels", MIT 15.097 Course Notes by Cynthia Rudin, URL: https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/sloan-school-of-management/15-097-prediction-machine-learning-and-statistics-spring-2012/lecture-notes/MIT15_097S12_lec13.pdf)

In [224]:
def rbf_kernel(x,y,sigma):
    return np.exp((-np.linalg.norm(x-y)**2)/sigma)

Compare the dot product and the kernel function - notice that the kernel never goes above 1. This suggests that in the prediction, we need to explicitly add the intercept b and not include it in the kernel calculations which we sum up over the number of the support vectors that define the hyperplane. Naively substituting the dot product by the kernel in the prediction function would give us all predictions as 1, beecause the sign of any value of the exponent function (which is how we define the kernel) is positive.

In [247]:
# define function to calculate hinge loss
def compute_cost_kernel(W, X, y, sigma, regul_strength=1e5):
    n = X.shape[0]
    distances = 1 - y * (rbf_kernel(X, W, sigma))  
#     distances = 1 - y * (rbf_kernel(X[:,:-1], W[:-1], sigma))  # if we do the intercept b separation
    distances[distances < 0] = 0  # equivalent to max(0, distance)
    hinge = regul_strength * (np.sum(distances) / n) # calculate the hinge loss function
    # calculate cost
    cost = 1 / 2 * np.dot(W, W) + hinge
    return cost

Below is an attempt to implement the algorithm with the derivative of the kernel because we need to separate the intercept b which is not in the higher dimensional space - the goal is to optimise the weights that define the hyperplane and the intercept b separately. However it takes up a lot of computational power, so it could not be used for scanning over the parameters sigma. For the parameters of sigma that were tried out, it gives out all predictions of 1's.

In [248]:
# calculate gradient of cost
def derivative_kernel(W, x_i, sigma):
    return rbf_kernel(W,x_i,sigma)* ((-2/sigma) * (W-x_i))
    

def calculate_cost_gradient_kernel_costly(W, X_batch, y_batch, sigma, regul_strength=1e5):
    # if only one example is passed
    if type(y_batch) == np.float64:
        y_batch = np.asarray([y_batch])
        X_batch = np.asarray([X_batch])  # gives multidimensional array
    distance = 1 - (y_batch * rbf_kernel(X_batch[:,:-1], W[:-1], sigma)) 
    dw = np.zeros(len(W[:-1]))
    db = 0

    for ind, d in enumerate(distance):
        if max(0, d)==0:
            dw += W[:-1]
            db -= 0
        else:
            dw += W[:-1] - (regul_strength * y_batch[ind] * derivative_kernel(W[:-1], X_batch[ind][:-1], sigma))
            db -= regul_strength * y_batch[ind]  # update the gradient of b to optimise b implicitly

    dw = dw/len(y_batch)  # average it
    db = db/len(y_batch)
    
    return dw, db

Instead, we perform the optimisation using this gradient descent function.

In [249]:
# calculate gradient of cost
def calculate_cost_gradient_kernel(W, X_batch, y_batch, sigma, regul_strength=1e5):
    # if only one example is passed
    if type(y_batch) == np.float64:
        y_batch = np.asarray([y_batch])
        X_batch = np.asarray([X_batch])  # gives multidimensional array
  
    distance = 1 - (y_batch * rbf_kernel(X_batch, W, sigma))
    dw = np.zeros(len(W))

    for ind, d in enumerate(distance):
        if max(0, d)==0:
            di = W
        else:
            di = W - (regul_strength * y_batch[ind] * X_batch[ind])
        dw += di

    dw = dw/len(y_batch)  # average
    return dw
In [299]:
def sgd_kernel(X, y, sigma, max_iterations=2000, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-5, regul_strength=1e5, print_outcome=False):
  # write the initial conditions for the weights
  weights = np.zeros(X.shape[1])
  nth = 0
  # initialise starting cost as infinity
  prev_cost = np.inf
  
  # stochastic gradient descent
  for iteration in range(1, max_iterations):
      # shuffle to prevent repeating update cycles
      np.random.shuffle([X, y])
      for ind, x in enumerate(X):
          ascent = calculate_cost_gradient_kernel(weights, x, y[ind], sigma, regul_strength)
          weights = weights - (learning_rate * ascent) # use the gradients of w in ascent for hyperplane optimisation  
               
            
#           if using the separation of weights and intercept b to optimise it implicitly, using the gradient of b for intercept optimisation
#           ascent_w, db = calculate_cost_gradient_kernel_costly(weights, x, y[ind], sigma, regul_strength)
#           weights[:-1] = weights[:-1] - (learning_rate * ascent_w)  # use the gradients of w for hyperplane optimisation
#           weights[-1] = weights[-1] - (learning_rate * db)  # use the gradient of b for intercept optimisation


      # convergence check on 2^n'th iteration
      if iteration==2**nth or iteration==max_iterations-1:
          # compute cost
          cost = compute_cost_kernel(weights, X, y, sigma, regul_strength) 
          if print_outcome:
            print("Iteration is: {}, Cost is: {}".format(iteration, cost))
          # stop criterion
          if abs(prev_cost - cost) < stop_criterion * prev_cost:
              return weights
          
          prev_cost = cost
          nth += 1
  
  return weights

Define a function to get the prediction for the kernelised SVM.

In [251]:
def predict_rgd_SVM(W, X, y, sigma):
    y_preds = np.array([])
    for i in range(X.shape[0]):
        y_pred = np.sign(  rbf_kernel(X[i,:-1], W[:-1], sigma) + np.dot(X[i,-1],W[-1]) )  # W[-1] is the intercept b of the hyperplane

#         y_pred = np.sign(  rbf_kernel(X[i,:-1], W[:-1], sigma) + W[-1])
#         y_pred = np.sign(np.dot(X[i], W))
        y_preds = np.append(y_preds, y_pred)
    return y_preds

Now perform the grid search and 5-fold CV.

In [305]:
def cross_val_evaluate(data, data_test, num_folds, sigma):
  folds = cross_val_split(data, num_folds)
  F1_scores = []
  F1_test = []
  TPR_test = []
  FPR_test = []
  for i in range(len(folds)):
    #print('Fold', i+1)
    # define the training set
    train_set = np.delete(np.asarray(folds).reshape(len(folds), folds[0].shape[0], folds[0].shape[1]), i, axis=0)
    train_folds = train_set.reshape(len(train_set)*train_set[0].shape[0], train_set[0].shape[1])
    
    X_train = train_folds[:,:-1]
    y_train = train_folds[:,-1]
    
    # define the validation set
    val_fold = folds[i]
    X_val = val_fold[:,:-1]
    y_val = val_fold[:,-1]
    
    X_test = data_test[:,:-1]
    y_test = data_test[:,-1]

    # train the model
    W = sgd_kernel(X_train, y_train, sigma=0.5, max_iterations=2000, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-3, regul_strength=1e7, print_outcome=False)

    # get y_pred
    y_pred = predict_rgd_SVM(W,X_val,y_val,sigma)
    # get y_pred
    y_pred_test = predict_rgd_SVM(W,X_test,y_test,sigma)
    
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the validation fold
    tp, fp, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_val,y_pred,print_info=False)
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    F1 = f1_score(precision, recall,print_info=False)
    F1_scores.append(F1)
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the test set
    tp_test, fp_test, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred_test,print_info=False)
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    
    F1_t = f1_score(precision, recall,print_info=False)
    F1_test.append(F1_t)
    
    TPR_test.append(recall)
    fpr = fp / (fp + tn) if (fp + tn)!=0 else 0
    FPR_test.append(fpr)
    

  return F1_scores, F1_test, TPR_test, FPR_test

plt.show()

We see that in each of the five folds, the predictions are always 1, thus even modifying the parameter of the kernel does not change it. In addition to the kernel being set to 0 and the intercept b being positive thus making the prediction 1, it is useful to think why we get the positive value of b in this case. It may be due to the predictions in training data being generally 1's, while the folds are smaller subsets of the training data, and the hard-margin SVMs does not separate well data that is non-linearly separable.

Since the scores do not change, there is not much use to compute the ROC curve as there is no rates of false positives against the true positives as they remain constant. It would be much more meaningful if we drew it having varying rates of false positives and true negatives, because in that case we could see how well out model is distinguishing between the classes, verying the hyperparameters. It would be most reasonable to choose the hyperparameters for which the true positive rate is largest and falsee positive rate is smallest - that is the point where the line of FP rate and TP rate is furthest from the random diagonal line which represents random sampling.

In [314]:

We can see that the point at 1,1 is not better than random sampling, and this is due to the fact that we get all predictions as 1's.

It may also be that the Gaussian kernel is not well suited for this dataset. It is may be non-separable even after implementing the Gaussian kernel trick as we have high-dimensional variables. However, additional checks and alternative implementations of optimisation would be helpful to explore the data and determine whether it is more suitable for the kernelised SVM.

Additionally, the issue may be the implementation of stochastic gradient descent, it would have been useful to implement the same calculations with Quadratic Programming packages for convex optimisation to use the alphas (Lagrange multipliers) directly to determine the support vectors that will contribute to the definition of the hyperplane. The support vectors will correspond to non-zero alpha terms, using the complimentary slackness condition. Below is a sketch of the implementation. (I started doing this before the instructors specified that we are not allowed to use optimisation packages)

In [315]:
def model():
    # perform QP (cvxopt package for example) with our constraint, get the alphas
    # get the support vectors y_sv 
    # get the sub-kernel matrix K, where K[i,j] = rbf_kernel(X[i], X[j])            
    # get sv are the indices of the suppoort vectors
    # calculate the intercept b explicitly looping through the support vectors
    for k in range(sum(sv)): # number of support vectors sv
        b = b + y_sv[k] - np.sum(K[indices[k],sv] * alpha * y_sv) # calculate the intercept b explicitly 
                                                                # using the non-zero Lagrange multipliers alpha
                                                                # and the sub-kernels for that support vector
    return sv, b
In [316]:
# define a prediction function for kernel SVMs
# the prediction is the sign of the output of this function: kernel(x,w) + b
def predict_kerSVM(X, y, alpha, support_vectors, b):
    y_preds = np.array([])
    for i in range(X.shape[0]):
        sum = 0
        for j in range(len(support_vectors)):  # no assumption that we have two support vectors here
            sum = sum + alpha[j] * y[j] * rbf_kernel(x,support_vectors[j],sigma=0.5) #np.sign(np.dot(X[i], W))
        y_pred = sum + b  # add the intercept b explicitly
        y_preds = np.append(y_preds, y_pred)
    return y_preds

Mastery Component¶

Hard vs Soft margin¶

In our implementation, we retrieve the hard margin for high regularisation strengths, while for smaller ones we have a soft margin.

For a $\lambda$ that is too small, the model is not 'punished' for the errors enough, so expect the model to be too general and not fit well, and for a large $\lambda$, the importance of the error is inflated and we get good in-sample accuracy but we overfit the data. We have already seen in the exploration before the implementation of the hard-margin SVM that we do get higher accuracy in both the training and test sets with a small regularisation strength. We will now explore this in more detail, using the sigmoid kernel (multilayer perceptron) in the comparison of the hard and soft margin SVMs.

The sigmoid kernel is most commonly described in the literature as only being positive definite (a must condition for extra-dimensionality in this case) for some parameter values, and in general it is not seen as better than RBF or linear kernels. (Source: "A Study on Sigmoid Kernels for SVM and the Training of non-PSD Kernels by SMO-type Methods", Hsuan-Tien Lin and Chih-Jen Lin, National Taiwan University, URL: http://home.caltech.edu/~htlin/publication/doc/tanh.pdf)

In [318]:
# parameters - slope (commonly 1/N, N is the dimension of data) and intercept c
def kernel_sigmoid(x,y,slope,c):
    return np.tanh(-slope*np.dot(x,y)+c)

In this graph, we explore thee behaviour of the kernel function and its sensitivity to the variations of the hyperparameters. These graphs are not ideal because in each scanning, we had set the other hyperparameter as constant. Notice however that there is a more dramatic change from -1 to 1 when we vary the slope. Although of course depending on the input vectors, we can also get a positive value when the slope or c is negative.

Interestingly, it has been shown that when the slope and intercept c are in a certain limited range for some a > 0, r < 0, we essentially have a similar behaviour to the RBF kernel. (Source: https://www.csie.ntu.edu.tw/~cjlin/papers/tanh.pdf)

define the functions with sigmoid kernel¶
In [276]:
# define function to calculate hinge loss
def compute_cost_sigmoid(W, X, y, slope, c, regul_strength):
    n = X.shape[0]
    distances = 1 - y * (kernel_sigmoid(X, W, slope=0.01, c=0.25))  
    distances[distances < 0] = 0  # equivalent to max(0, distance)
    hinge = regul_strength * (np.sum(distances) / n) # calculate the hinge loss function
    # calculate cost
    cost = 1 / 2 * np.dot(W, W) + hinge
    return cost
In [277]:
# calculate gradient of cost
def calculate_cost_gradient_sigmoid(W, X_batch, y_batch, slope, c, regul_strength):
    if type(y_batch) == np.float64:      # if only one example is passed
        y_batch = np.asarray([y_batch])
        X_batch = np.asarray([X_batch])  # gives multidimensional arry
    distance = 1 - (y_batch * kernel_sigmoid(X_batch, W, slope, c))
    dw = np.zeros(len(W))

    for ind, d in enumerate(distance):
        if max(0, d)==0:
            di = W
        else:
            di = W - (regul_strength * y_batch[ind] * X_batch[ind])
        dw += di
    dw = dw/len(y_batch)  # average
    return dw
In [278]:
# define stochastic gradient descent to get weights that define our hyperplane

def sgd_sigmoid(X, y, slope, c, max_iterations=2000, stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-5, regul_strength=1e5, print_outcome=False):
  # write the initial conditions for the weights
  weights = np.zeros(X.shape[1])
  nth = 0
  prev_cost = np.inf  # initialise starting cost as infinity
  for iteration in range(1, max_iterations):  # stochastic gradient descent
      np.random.shuffle([X, y])  # shuffle to prevent repeating update cycles
      for ind, x in enumerate(X):
          ascent = calculate_cost_gradient_sigmoid(weights, x, y[ind], slope, c, regul_strength)
          weights = weights - (learning_rate * ascent)

      # convergence check on 2^n'th iteration
      if iteration==2**nth or iteration==max_iterations-1:
          # compute cost
          cost = compute_cost_sigmoid(weights, X, y, slope, c, regul_strength) 
          if print_outcome:
            print("Iteration is: {}, Cost is: {}".format(iteration, cost))
          # stop criterion
          if abs(prev_cost - cost) < stop_criterion * prev_cost:
              return weights
          
          prev_cost = cost
          nth += 1
  
  return weights
In [279]:
# define prediction function
def predict_sigmoid_SVM(W, X, y, slope, c):
    y_preds = np.array([])
    for i in range(X.shape[0]):
        y_pred = np.sign( kernel_sigmoid(X[i,:-1], W[:-1], slope, c) + np.dot(X[i,-1],W[-1]) )  # W[-1] is the intercept b of the hyperplane
        
#         y_pred = np.sign(  kernel_sigmoid(X[i,:-1], W[:-1], slope, c) + W[-1])
#         y_pred = np.sign(np.dot(X[i], W))
        y_preds = np.append(y_preds, y_pred)
    return y_preds

The results for the hard margin seem to be independent from the parameters, but in the soft margin case, varying the intercept does seem to affect the balance between the posittive and negative predictions: for positive values, we get all positive predictions on the testing set, for very small (of order $10^{-5}$) positive and negative values, we have a combination of both positive and negative predictions, while for negative values we only get negative predictions (-1 corresponding to dependent classification variable 0).

In what follows, we will perform a grid parameter search with 5-fold cross-validation on the soft margin sigmoid kernel SVM model to find the optimal hyperparameters.

In [383]:
def cross_val_evaluate_sigmoid(data, data_test, num_folds, regul_strength, slope, c, print_info = True):
  folds = cross_val_split(data, num_folds)
  F1_scores = []
  F1_test = []
  for i in range(len(folds)):
    if print_info:
        print('Fold', i+1)
    # define the training set
    train_set = np.delete(np.asarray(folds).reshape(len(folds), folds[0].shape[0], folds[0].shape[1]), i, axis=0)
    train_folds = train_set.reshape(len(train_set)*train_set[0].shape[0], train_set[0].shape[1])
    
    X_train = train_folds[:,:-1]
    y_train = train_folds[:,-1]
    
    # define the validation set
    val_fold = folds[i]
    X_val = val_fold[:,:-1]
    y_val = val_fold[:,-1]
    
    X_test = data_test[:,:-1]
    y_test = data_test[:,-1]

    # train the model
    W = sgd_sigmoid(X_train,y_train, slope, c, max_iterations=2000, 
                    stop_criterion=0.01, learning_rate=1e-3, regul_strength=0.01, print_outcome=print_info)
    # get y_pred
    y_pred = predict_sigmoid_SVM(W,X_val,y_val,slope,c)
    # get y_pred
    y_pred_test = predict_sigmoid_SVM(W,X_test,y_test,slope,c)
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the validation fold
    tp, fp, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_val,y_pred,print_info=False)
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    F1 = f1_score(precision, recall,print_info=False)
    F1_scores.append(F1)
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the test set
    tp, fp, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred_test,print_info=False)
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    F1_t = f1_score(precision, recall,print_info=False)
    F1_test.append(F1_t)
    
    

  return F1_scores, F1_test

In [370]:
plt.plot(cs,scan_test)
plt.xaxis('intercept c')
plt.yaxis('F1 score')
plt.show()
Out[370]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1a224c5810>]

We do seem to get different F1 scores when we vary the c intercept parameter in the sigmoid kernel function, but it does not reach better accuracies than the prediction where we get all positive preedictions. This suggests there may be fundamental flaws in the optimisation method or in the tuning of other parameters that were not considered in the optimisation.

In [375]:
slopes = np.arange(-10,1,0.1)
# cs = [-0.01,-0.001,-0.0008,-0.0005,-0.0003,0]
c = 0.01

hyperparams = [0,0]

scan = []
scan_test = []
for sl in slopes:
    print('slope =',sl)
    F1_scores, F1_test = cross_val_evaluate_sigmoid(data_train, data_test, 5, 0.01, sl, c)
    scan.append(np.average(F1_scores))
    scan_test.append(np.average(F1_test))

slope = -10.0
