These hyperparameters are not very meaningful since normally they are positive, and moreover the score that determines their choice is the one for the predictions of all 1's. This suggests that the implementation of the optimisation has errors.

A state-of-the-art alternative to modifying the code provided¶

(in other words, a hacky way to implement the soft margin part of the Mastery material)¶

A way to go around the failing optimisation in the kernelised soft-margin SVM is to implement a different gradient descent method, namely the Pegasos algorithm, first introduced by Shalev-Shwartz et al. in 2011. (Source: Shalev-Shwartz, S., Singer, Y., Srebro, N. et al. Pegasos: primal estimated sub-gradient solver for SVM. Math. Program. 127, 330 (2011). https://doi.org/10.1007/s10107-010-0420-4)

The authors note that it is usually a constrained quadratic programming optimisation problem, but at its core, it originates from an unconstrained minimisation of the hinge loss function. In that paper, it has a slightly different formulation because the penalty term $\lambda$ is written for the norm of the vector $\boldsymbol w$ that is essentially our classification model: $$ L(\boldsymbol w) = \frac{\lambda}{2} \| \boldsymbol w \|^2 + \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n l (\boldsymbol w, (\boldsymbol x, y)) \ $$ with $ l = \max \big( 0, 1-y_i \langle \boldsymbol w, \boldsymbol x \rangle ) \big)$ (*), and the inner product of w or x can be either linear or non-linear (kernelised). When kernelised, it is computed as $$ \langle \boldsymbol w, \boldsymbol x \rangle = \sum_{i\in I_t} \alpha_i \langle \boldsymbol x_i, \boldsymbol x_j \rangle, $$ and computing the norm of the weights that are the parameters of the separation hyperplane we seek to minimise also using the Lagrange multipliers alpha: $$ \| \boldsymbol w_t \|^2 = \sum_{i\in I_t} \alpha_i \alpha_j \langle \boldsymbol x_i, \boldsymbol x_j \rangle,$$ where the index $t$ represeents the fact that we are only training on a sub-sample of the training examples.

The crucial modification in this stochastic gradient descent method is that they do a projection step at each step of the calculation of the gradient. The projection is that of the weight w onto an L2 ball of radius $1/\sqrt{\lambda}$. Moreover, it does not use the full training examples, but only a sub-sample k of them to compute an approximate sub-gradient. This significantly reduces the computational power and allows for parallel computation. Also note that the learning rate is set to $\eta_t = \frac{1}{\lambda t}$.

The implementation of the for the linear and non-linear kernel case can be readily found on github for various programming languages; I rely on the pseudocode provided by the authors and a simple and straightforward implementation in the repository https://github.com/h44rd/Pegasos/blob/master/pegasos.py.

To better understand the updatee rule in this case, write thee update rules for the stochastic sub-gradient algorithm (it is stochastic because the training data is sampled at random):

if $ y_i f(\boldsymbol x_{i})<1:$ $$\boldsymbol w_{t+1} = \boldsymbol w_{t} - \eta(\lambda \boldsymbol w_{t} - y_i \boldsymbol x_{i}),$$ else: $$\boldsymbol w_{t+1} = \boldsymbol w_{t} - \eta \lambda \boldsymbol w_{t}, $$ where again $\eta$ is the learning rate.

Source: https://www.robots.ox.ac.uk/~az/lectures/ml/lect2.pdf

In [507]:
# define the linear SVM algorithm - training and testing

def train_nonkernel(X_train, y_train, T, lam):
    t = 1
    w = np.zeros(X_test[0].shape)  # initialise the weights array
    idx = np.random.permutation(len(X_train)) # permute the order of the indices
    for i in idx:  # iterate through the indices
        x, yi = X_train[i], y_train[i]  # get the predictor and outcome at index i
        nt  = 1.0/(lam*t)  # nt is the learning rate, t is incremented after each iteration of the index
        # these conditionals correspond to the max function l defined above (*)
        if yi * np.dot(w, x) < 1: 
            w = (1 - nt * lam) * w + nt * yi * x 
        elif yi * np.dot(w, x) >= 1:
            w = (1 - nt * lam) * w
        w = min(1, (1/(lam)**(1/2))/np.linalg.norm(w)) * w  # update the weights depending on the penalty term
        t += 1
    return w  # return the weights

def test_nonkernel(w, X_test, y_test):
    total = 0
    correct = 0
    preds = []  # init list to store predictions
    for (x,yi) in zip(X_test, y_test):
        pred = np.dot(w, x)
        preds.append(pred)  # append prediction
        if yi * pred > 0:
            correct += 1
        total += 1
    return correct, total, np.sign(preds)  # output predictions as signs of the y to get -1,1 values

Prepare the data and parameters. Note that the performance of the algorithm depends on the parameter lambda and, importantly, does not depend on the size of the data.

We seee that the F1 score of the linear SVM is not great, suggesting that our data is indeed non linearly separable. Implement the non-linear soft margin SVM with both the Gaussian and sigmoid kernels for a qualitative discussion about their performance.

In [529]:
# define the gaussian RBF kernel
def kernel_rbf(x, y, sigma):
     return np.exp((-np.linalg.norm(x-y)**2)/sigma)

# parameters - slope (commonly 1/N, N is the dimension of data) and intercept c
def kernel_sigmoid(x,y,slope,c):
    return np.tanh(-slope*np.dot(x,y)+c)
    
def train_kernel(X_train, y_train, lam, T, sigma, slope, c, kernel):
    aplhas = np.zeros(len(X_train))
    idx = np.random.permutation(len(X_train)) # permute
    t = 0
    for i in idx:
        x, yi = X_train[i], y_train[i]
        s = 0
        for j in range(len(X_train)):
            if kernel=='rbf':
                s += aplhas[j]*y_train[j]*kernel_rbf(x, X_train[j], sigma)
            if kernel=='sigmoid':
                s += aplhas[j]*y_train[j]*kernel_sigmoid(x, X_train[j], slope, c)
        if yi*(1/lam)*s < 1:
            aplhas[i] = aplhas[i] + 1
        if t >= T:
            break
        else:
            t += 1
#         if t%100==0:
#             print("Iteration of Kernel Training: ", t)
    return aplhas  # return the alphas - the non-zero ones identify which support vectors define our separation hyperplane


def test_kernel(alphas, lam, X_test, y_test, X_train, y_train, T, sigma, slope, c, kernel):
    total = 0
    correct = 0
    t = 0
    preds = []
    for (x,yi) in zip(X_test, y_test):
        s = 0
        for j in range(len(X_train)):
            if kernel=='rbf':
                s += alphas[j]*y_train[j]*kernel_rbf(x, X_train[j], sigma)
            if kernel=='sigmoid':
                s += alphas[j]*y_train[j]*kernel_sigmoid(x, X_train[j], slope, c)
        if (yi*(1/lam)*s < 1):
            correct += 1
        preds.append(s)
        total += 1
        if t >= T:
            break
        else:
            t += 1
#         if t%50==0:
#             print("Testing iteration: ", t)
    return correct, total, preds

TP: 67 FP: 45 TN: 8 FN: 80
F1 score : 0.5173745173745173

Using this algorithm, we ge a worse accuracy and F1 score for the sigmoid kernel. This may be due to a poor choice of parameters.

Although having a better score and accuracy for the sigmoid kernel clearly suggests that the data is separable in the extra dimensional space. We now perform a 5-fold CV and grid search for the optimal hyperparameters for the soft-margin sigmoid kernel SVM.

In [530]:
def cross_val_evaluate(data, data_test, num_folds, lam, slope, c):
  
  folds = cross_val_split(data, num_folds)  # we get transposed folds, data is (800, 11) dimensional

  F1_scores = [] # for score on validation folds
  F1_test = [] # on test set (most important one)

  for i in range(len(folds)):
    print('Fold', i+1)
    # define the training set
    train_set = np.delete(np.asarray(folds).reshape(len(folds), folds[0].shape[0], folds[0].shape[1]), i, axis=0)
    train_folds = train_set.reshape(len(train_set)*train_set[0].shape[0], train_set[0].shape[1])
    
    X_train = train_folds[:,:-1]
    y_train = train_folds[:,-1]
    
    # define the validation set
    val_fold = folds[i]
    X_val = val_fold[:,:-1]
    y_val = val_fold[:,-1]
    
    X_test = data_test[:,:-1]
    y_test = data_test[:,-1]

    # train the model
    T = 1000 # number of iterations for training
    sigma = 0.5 # will not be used, rbf param
    alphas = train_kernel(X_train, y_train, lam, 10000, sigma, slope, c, kernel='sigmoid')
    
    # get predictions
    _, _, y_pred_val = test_kernel(alphas, lam, X_val, y_val, X_train, y_train, T, sigma, slope, c, kernel='sigmoid')  # get y_pred on validation fold
    _, _, y_pred_test = test_kernel(alphas, lam, X_test, y_test, X_train, y_train, T, sigma, slope, c, kernel='sigmoid')  # get y_pred on test set
    
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the validation fold
    tp, fp, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_val,np.sign(y_pred_val))
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    F1 = f1_score(precision, recall)
    F1_scores.append(F1)
    
    # evaluate with F1 score on the test set
    tp, fp, tn, fn = confusion_matrix(y_test,np.sign(y_pred_test))
    precision, recall = prec_rec(tp, fp, tn, fn)
    F1_t = f1_score(precision, recall)
    F1_test.append(F1_t)

  return F1_scores, F1_test
In [544]:
# get stacked training and testing data to do the folds
y_train_peg = (np.zeros((1,800))+y_train_peg).T
y_test_peg = (np.zeros((1,200))+y_test_peg).T
data_train = np.hstack((X_train_peg,y_train_peg))  
data_test = np.hstack((X_test_peg,y_test_peg))

# set parameters
lam = 1
cs = np.linspace(0.01,0.03,4)
slopes = np.linspace(1/100,1,4)

max_val = 0
max_test = 0
list_params_val = [0,0]  # [slope, c]
list_params_test = [0,0] 
for c in cs:
    print('c',c)
    for slope in slopes:
        print('slope',slope)
        F1_val, F1_test = cross_val_evaluate(data_train, data_test, 5, lam, slope, c)
        F1_scores = np.average(F1_val)
        if F1_scores>max_val:
            max_val = F1_scores
            list_params_val = [slope,c]
                
        F1_test = np.average(F1_test)
        if F1_test>max_test:
            max_test = F1_test
            list_params_test = [slope,c]

In [547]:
cs = np.linspace(0.001,0.005,4)
slopes = np.linspace(1/1000,1/200,4)

max_val = 0
max_test = 0
list_params_val = [0,0]  # [slope, c]
list_params_test = [0,0] 
for c in cs:
    print('c',c)
    for slope in slopes:
        print('slope',slope)
        F1_val, F1_test = cross_val_evaluate(data_train, data_test, 5, lam, slope, c)
        F1_scores = np.average(F1_val)
        if F1_scores>max_val:
            max_val = F1_scores
            list_params_val = [slope,c]
                
        F1_test = np.average(F1_test)
        if F1_test>max_test:
            max_test = F1_test
            list_params_test = [slope,c]

It looks like the sigmoid kernel does not lead to a good separation of the data and therefore a good hyperplane is not defined to separate the data, even using the sigmoid kernel. It ends up overpredicting positive values. A better option is the RBF kernel.
